THE TANK CAR LEAKED ONLY WHEN MOVED, THEREFORE THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED TO TRACK NUMBER 40 TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE LEAKAGE. DAMAGED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR INSPECTION. FREIGHT LOADERS NEED TO BE AWARE OF POTENTIAL HAZARDS ON THE FLOOR WHICH COULD CAUSE DAMAGE TO FREIGHT.

THE FORWARD MOTION OF THE VEHICLE AS WELL AS AIRFLOW CONTRIBUTED TO THE TOPMOST BOXES ON THE REAR PALLET BEING BLOWN OFF OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE ON THE HIGHWAY.  THE IMPACT OF THE FALL FROM THE VEHICLE AS WELL WAS THE BOXES BEING HIT BE ONCOMING VEHICULAR TRAFFIC CONTRIBUTED TO THE SPILLAGE OF THE BAIT DEVICES ON THE HIGHWAY.

THE FOUR UNSEALED PAILS WERE OVERPACKED IN A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM AND LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER.  THE SPENT ABSORBENT WAS SWEPT UP, PACKED INTO A 30 GALLON POLY PAIL, AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF PROPERLY AT A LATER TIME.

column168: OUR VEHICLE WAS EXITING TO A WEIGHT STATION WHEN A MOTORIST INFORMED HIM THAT SOMETHING WAS LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER.  THE WEIGHT STATION OFFICER INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER TO PULL UP ON THE SCALES.  DUE TO THE OFFENSIVE ODOR OF THE LEAKING LIQUID, HE THEN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER PULL AROUND BACK AND CALL A EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM.  THE CARGO WAS THIOGLYCOLIC ACID STORED IN 55 GALLON BARRELS ON PALLETS. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT AND HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED FIRST AND KEPT THE SPILL UNTIL ENSTAT OF CULPEPER, VIRGINIA RESPONDED AND BROKE THE SEAL ON THE TRAILER.  ENSTAT DISCOVERED THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED FORWARD AND SOME OF THE DRUMS HAD FALLEN OFF THE FORWARD PALLET AND STRUCK A PROTRUDING NAIL.  COMMENTS FROM PERSONNEL ON THE SCENE INDICATED THAT THE CARGO WAS IMPROPERLY BLOCKED FOR TRANSPORT BY THE SHIPPER.  ENSTAT TOOK CHARGE AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITHOUT PERSONAL INJURY OR HARM TO THE ENVIRONMENT.

column168: TANK CAR PTLX 120093 WAS BEING CLASSIFIED  AT THE ILLINOIS CENTRAL CHAMPAIGN YARD WHEN SWITCH CREW NOTICED THERE WAS A LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR.  A CONTAMINATED BUCKET WAS HUNG UNDER THE CAR TO CATCH PRODUCT AND CAR WAS MOVED TO THE NUMBER 10 TRACK IN "C" YARD NORTH END.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY ILLINOIS CENTRAL MECHANICAL PERSONNEL THAT THE INNER LINER OF THE CAR HAD FAILED AND ALLOWED HYDROCHLORIC ACID TO GET TO THE TANK AND EAT A HOLE.  CENTRAL STATE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO HANDLE DECONTAMINATION AND CLEANUP.  THEY ALSO TRANSFERRED THE LOADED TANK CAR TO TANK TRUCKS SUPPLIED BY REAGENT CHEMICAL.  AFTER THE TRANSFER A WOODEN PLUG WAS PUT IN THE HOLE TO KEEP ANY RESIDUE FROM LEAKING FROM TANK. REAGENT CHEMICAL SENT RESCAR TO THE SCENE ON 10/8/97 AND THEY CUT OFF THE WOODEN PLUG AND WELDED A PATCH OVER THE HOLE.  ON 10/17/97 REAGENT RECEIVED AUTHORIZATION FROM FRA TO HOME SHOP CAR FOR REPAIRS.  AUTHORIZATION FRA-9710098.

column168: THE OPERATOR WAS ATTEMPTING TO DRIVE OVER A CONTAINMENT DIKE WALL WITH APPROXIMATELY A 10% GRADE.  AS THE VACUUM TRUCK REACHED THE TOP OF THE DIKE WALL THE LOAD SHIFTED TO THE REAR OF THE TRUCK (NO BAFFLES WERE INSTALLED), LIFTING THE STIRRING WHEELS OFF THE GROUND AND SHIFTING THE FRONT OF THE TRUCK OFF THE ROADBED.  AS THE DRIVE WHEELS CRESTED OVER THE TOP OF THE DRIVE.  THE LOAD SHIFTED FORWARD AND TO THE RIGHT, ROLLING THE TRUCK OFF THE ROAD AND DOWN THE EMBANKMENT.  THE DOT 412 CERTIFIED 3000 GALLON TANK AND ASSOCIATED ROLLOVER PROTECTION DID NOT FAIL AND PREVENTED DAMAGE TO THE TANK SYSTEM AND ALSO PREVENTED A COMPLETE ROLLOVER OF THE TRUCK. THE PRODUCT IN THE 3000 GALLON VACUUM TANK WAS NOT RELEASED DURING THE ROLLOVER, HOWEVER APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS WERE RELEASED THEN RECOVERED DURING THE TRANSFER OPERATIONS TO ANOTHER VACUUM TRUCK.  THIS PRODUCT WAS "WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (GASOLINE AND WATER), UN 1203. THE MATERIALS WERE CLEANED UP AND PRODUCT RECOVERED AND DISPOSED OF IN AN ONSITE TANK SYSTEM WITH NO RELEASE INTO WATERWAYS OR THE ENVIRONMENT.

column168: UNLOADING TRAILER WHEN DOCKMEN NOTICED BLACK DUST. DOCKMEN NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR. SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED CHEMTREX AND FIRE DEPARTMENT TO HAVE THEIR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM COME AND EVALUATE CHEMICAL FOR HAZARDOUS PROPERTIES. AREA OF DOCK CLOSED OFF UNTIL SUCH TIME IT WAS DEEMED SAFE TO CONTINUE TO CLEAN UP.

PAIL WAS STRUCK BY A PALLET JACK AS THE DRIVER WAS GOING AROUND THE CORNER. THE DRIVER FAILED TO MOVE THE PAIL FAR ENOUGH AWAY FROM THE JACK IN CASE THE JACK MOVED, WHICH IT DID. THE FREIGHT WAS BRACED BY OTHER FREIGHT. IT WAS A SMALL 2 GALLON PAIL. FLOOR DRY WAS USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND SODA ASH WAS PUT DOWN TO NEUTRALIXE THE MATERIAL. IT WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL. CLARK ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE CONTACTED TO DISPOSE OF THE MATERIAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELLED ON THE PROPER WAY TO BLOCK AND BRACE ALL FREIGHT TO PREVENT ANY FUTURE ACCIDENTS. THE DRIVER WAS ALSO GIVEN A LETTER OF INSTRUCTION FOR FAILING TO FOLLOW PROPER COMPANY PROCEDURES.
column172: Pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: DRIVER WAS HOOKING UP TO LOAD. HE DID NOT HAVE THE RIGHT CONNECTIONS HANDY. HE SEARCHED THROUGH THE TRUCK AND FOUND SOME OLD CONNECTIONS. PUTTING THEM TOGETHER OPENED THE VALVE. THE HOSE CAME LOOSE AT CONNECTION. THE NECESSARY CLEANUP WAS HANDLED. TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS LIKE THIS, TRAINING WAS DONE WITH ALL EMPLOYEES TO MAKE SURE THAT THEY HAD THE RIGHT EQUIPMENT IN GOOD WORKING CONDITION. IF NOT, DO NOT LOAD UNTIL RIGHT EQUIPMENT WAS BROUGHT OUT TO THEM.

column168: AN ILLINOIS CENTRAL BRAKEMAN NOTICED VAPOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 061076 IN OUR YARD AT GEISMAR, LA. THIS TANK WAS JUST PULLED FROM BASF PLANT AT GEISMAR, LA. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND SENT A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THEIR PLANT. BASF REPRESENTATIVE FOUND THE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE FLANGE TO BE LOOSE. BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND CAR WAS RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.

JOHN HILL WAS LOADING A LARGE CRATE OF MOTORCYCLES (PRO#82201658-JIMMY'S CYCLE SHOP, BASSETT, VA) AND HE WAS TOLD BY THE SUPERVISOR TO LOAD IN NOSE OF TRAILER AND HE DIDN'T KNOW THAT ANY OTHER FREIGHT WAS ON THE TRAILER. HE COULD NOT SEE AHEAD AND RAN OVER A TWENTY (20) GALLON PLASTIC PAIL AND A PART ON THE MOTORCYCLE PUNCHED A HOLE IN IT. ALL THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT INSIDE THE TRAILER AND DRIPPED THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR ONTO THE GROUND.

BOX OF FOUR (4) BOTTLES OF HEXANE WAS PLACED IN NOSE OF TRAILER. FORKLIFT BLADE PROTRUDED PAST THE END OF NEXT PALLET TO BE LOADED. THE BLADE PUNCTURED ONE OF THE BOTTLES. THE TRAILER WAS EVACUATED AND MATERIAL REMOVED FROM TRAILER WITH FLOOR DRY AND GLOVES.

BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING FROM THE TOP SIDE LIQUID VALVE. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE VALVE MOUNTING BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND THAT INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS FORCING PRODUCT OUT THE GAP BETWEEN THE VALVE BASE AND FLANGE ON THE CAR. THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY TWO TURNS EACH TO STOP THE RELEASE. THE CAR WAS NOT OVERLOADED AND HAD AN INTACT FRANGIBLE DISC. PRODUCT RELEASE WAS ESTIMATED AT 5 GALLONS IN TRACK 3006 AND 20 GALLONS AFTER BEING SWITCHED TO THE CONTAINMENT PIT TRACK. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS NEUTRALIZED BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR.

THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM THEN UNBOLTED AND OPENED THE MANWAY COVER TO VIEW THE LIQUID LEVEL IN TANK.  AFTER INSPECTING THE LIQUID LEVEL, THEY FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE MANWAY COVER AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  AT TIME OF MOVEMENT A SLOSHING ACTING OCCURRED WITHIN THE TANK AND PRODUCT LEAKED BETWEEN MANWAY RING AND COVER EXPOSING A TRANSPORTATION EMPLOYEE TO THE CHEMICAL.  EMPLOYEE WAS EXAMINED AS AN OUTPATIENT AT LOCAL HOSPITAL AND RELEASE WITHOUT ANY LOSS OF TIME FROM WORK.  CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED AND PROPERLY SECURED MANWAY.  CAR CONTINUED ENROUTE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: AT 1250 ON THE MORNING OF THURSDAY, 10/30/97, I RECEIVED A CALL AT MY HOUSE.  ONE OF TH MADIX EMPLOYEES (ENRIQUE GUTIERREZ OF THE SHIPPING DEPARTMENT) REPORTED TO ME THAT THERE WAS AT LEAST ONE DRUM LEAKING ON A PST TRUCK THAT HAD PULLED UP TO OUR DOCK TO BE UNLOADED.  THE DRIVER PULLED OUT OF THE WAY SO WE COULD USE THE DOCK.  I GOT IN MY CAR AND DROVE TO THE SITE. IN ADDITION OT THE CONTAMINATION INSIDE AN DON THE PST TRAILER, THERE WERE 3 AREAS OF CONTAMINATION OF MADIX PROPERTY.  ONE WHERE HE HAD ORIGINALLY PULLED UP ON CONCRETE, ONE WHERE HE PULLED OUT OF THE WAY ONTO A WHITE ROCK AND DIRT PARKING AREA, AND ONE WHERE HE REDOCKED TO UNLOAD (IT WAS ON CONCRETE, BUT IN A DIFFERENT PLACE).  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS A PAINT MANUFACTURED AND SHIPPED BY SPRAYLAT.  THEIR PRODUCT CODE FOR IT IS J2058.  IT IS A HIGH SOLIDS BAKING ENAMEL.  A FULL DRUM WEIGHED 654 POUNDS, AND THIS DRUM, AFTER WE INVERTED IT TO STOP THE LEAK, WEIGHED 618 POUNDS.  NO OTHER DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THIS MEANS 36 POUNDS OF PAINT WAS LEAKED INTO THE TRAILER, AND SOME OF IT FOUND ITS WAY OUT THE DOOR.  IT MADE A MESS MUCH BIGGER THAN 36 POUNDS WOULD SUGGEST.  THERE WAS A PAINT PUDDLE THE WIDTH OF THE TRAILER AND ABOUT 6 FEET UP THE LENGTH OF THE TRAILER ON THE INSIDE, AND PAINT HAD LEAKED DOW THE TRAILER STRUCTURE ONTO THE GROUND.  A DRUM, MARKED "1A2/Y1.2/100 USA/R1286/97/RL" WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING IN TWO PLACES ON THE BOTTOM STEEL PLATE (NOT AT THE SEAMS).  I COULD NOT FIND ANY FURTHER MANUFACTURER OR RECONDITIONER INFORMATION ON THE DRUM.  THE BOTTOM PLATE APPEARED TO CREASED IN A STRAIGHT LINE AS IF SOMETHING HAD PUSHED UP ON THE MIDDLE OF THE MIDDLE OF THE BOTTOM PLATED OF THE DRUM. PICTURES OF THE DRUM ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. column168: ON 10/23/1997, A DOCKWORKER WAS TRANSPORTING A TOTE TANK FROM OUR TRAILER TO OUR LOADING PLATFORM WHEN THE TOTE TOPPLED OVER CAUSING APPROX. 300 GALLONS OF LIQUID CONTAINING SODIUM NITRITE TO SPILL INTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ONTO THE ASPHALT YARD.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT  AND CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR (PETROLEUM RECOVERY SERVICES, INC) WERE CALLED WITHIN MINUTES OF THE SPILL.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT AND CLEAN - UP MATERIALS WERE RECOVERED BY PETRO CHEM AND ARE CONTAINED IN DRUM AT WILSON TRUCKING CORP. HAMPTON, VA FACILITY UNTIL PROPER DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS ARE COMPLETED.

BNSF SECURITY PERSONNEL FOUND LEAKING CAR DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION. RESPONDERS DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK . INSPECTION REVEALED THAT REPAIRS TO A HAND RAIL BRACKET HAD BEEN REFORMED WITH A WELDER.  THE CONCLUSION WAS DRAWN THAT THE HEAT FROM THE WELDING HAD COMPROMISED THE INNER TANK LINER, THUS PERMITTING PRODUCT TO CORRODE BOTTOM AREA OF TANK CAR TANK. DECONTAMINATION WAS REQUIRED AT THE DISCOVERY SITE , AND THE LAST 15 MILES OF RAIL ROUTE. SOIL AND TRACK MATERIALS WERE REMOVED AT THE SITE AND  A NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION WAS APPLIED TO THE RIGHT OF WAY.  THE CAR WAS TRANSLOADED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR BY THE CONSIGNEE'S TEAM.

column168: VEHICLE WAS NORTHBOUND ON I-181 IN J0HNSON CITY, TN, WHEN OUR DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE UNITS AND ROLLED OVER IN THE MEDIAN. THE TRAILER LOST LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT AS THE PRESSURE RELIEF SYSTEM "BURPED" TO RELIEVE THE TANK'S INTERNAL PRESSURE AFTER IMPACT. THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED IN BOTH DIRECTIONS FOR APPROXIMATELY 19 HOURS. THE TRAILER WAS OFF-LOADED AND SET UP RIGHT. TRACTOR WAS TOWED FROM THE SCENE. TRAILER WAS WATER-TIGHT AND TOWABLE. NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT. AREA OF THE SPILL WAS REMEDIATED. SPILL WASTE WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED. DRIVER WAS TREATED AT LOCAL HOSPITAL AND ARRESTED FOR DUI.

DRIVER PARKED ALONG SIDE OUR VEHICLE CALLED CHEMTREC WHICH NOTIFIED CARRIER. CARRIER RESPONDED CLOSING ALL VALVES AND CLEANED UP RELEASED MATERIAL WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.

MATERIAL WAS RELEASED FROM A LOOSE WASHOUT CAP AND THE RELEASE STOPPED WHEN CAP TIGHTENED. MATERIAL SOAKED THE INSULATION AND CONTINUED TO DRIP ON THE BOTTOM OF CARGO TANK. LOAD TRANSLOADED INTO ANOTHER CARGO TANK. DIAPER PLACED ON EMPTY CARGO TANK AND TRANSPORTED TO KNOXVILLE, TN. CARGO TANK TESTED AND BARREL NOT LEAKING. WASHOUT CAP INSPECTED.

NUTS ON INTERNAL VALVE LOOSE AND WRONG SUMP GASKET INSTALLED BY AN OUTSIDE REPAIR SHOP IN MARKHAM, IL. MAINTENANCE  REVIEW HELD WITH VENDOR SHOP ON 10/30/1997.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00PM ON 10/16/97, OUR DRIVER WAS LEAVING MARATHON OIL'S SITE AND ENTERED HWY 61. HE CROSSED OVER 2 SOUTHBOUND HWY 61 LANES AND ENTERED ONTO THE RIGHT HAND NORTHBOUND LANE. A FLAT BED WORK TRUCK CAME FROM BEHIND AND REAR-ENDED OUR TRACTOR/ TRAILER CAUSING THE CARGO TANK TO RUPTURE ON THE REAR. 250 GALLONS OF HI-SULFUR DIESEL LEAKED OUT. THE ACCIDENT WAS CONSIDERED THE FAULT OF THE OTHER DRIVER. ALL OF THE SPILLED DIESEL AND CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL AND REMEDIATION BY INDUSTRIAL CLEANUP INC.. THE CARGO TANK WAS TAKEN TO OUR OFFICE AT 2330 HWY 70, DONALDSONVILLE, LA 70346. FROM OUR POSITION, THE ACCIDENT COULD NOT BE AVOIDED; THEREFORE, NO CORRECTIVE OF PREVENTIVE ACTION WAS TAKEN.

ON 10//24/1997 AT APPROXIMATELY 14:30 HRS., I WAS ADVISED BY RUST INDUSTRIAL HEALTH AND SAFETY OF A POSSIBLE RELEASE OF A RQ WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID TOXIC NOS (RQ AMOUNT 1 LB.). THE FOLLOWING DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS WERE OBTAINED FROM STATEMENT FROM THE DRIVER, SUPERVISOR, PROJECT MANAGER AND THE HEALTH AND SAFETY MANAGER FROM RUST INDUSTRIAL. (TRANSPORTER). THE RUST DRIVER HAD BEEN ASSIGNED THE TASK  OF TRANSFERRING API/DAF SLUDGE FROM TOSCO WILMINGTON TO TOSCO CARSON. UPON ARRIVING AT THE DESTINATION, THE GUARD AT THE ATE ADVISED THE DRIVER THAT THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK WAS WET. THIS LED BOTH PARTIES TO BELIEVE THAT DURING TRANSPORTATION AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF PRODUCT HAD OCCURRED THROUGH A REAR PIPE IN THE TRAILER THAT HAD A CAM-LOCK CAP MISSING. THE GUARD NOTIFIED TOSCO OFFICIALS AND THE DRIVER NOTIFIED RUST OFFICIALS. THE TRUCK ROUTE FROM WILMINGTON TO CARSON HAD BEEN INSPECTED FOR ANY EVIDENCE OF THE SPILLED MATERIALS. THIS ROUTE WAS TRAVELED BY BOTH TRANSPORTER OFFICIALS AND EVIDENCE OF ANY SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NOT OBSERVE. THE ONLY OTHER ISSUE THAT COULD POSSIBLY POINT TO A SPILL WAS A DISCREPANCY IN THE WEIGHT TICKET OF WILMINGTON #363870 AND CARSON #21000 (APPROXIMATELY 160 LBS.). AT THIS TIME IT WAS DECIDED THAT AGENCY NOTIFICATION WAS APPROPRIATE. AT APPROX 1500 HRS ON 10/24/97 NRC WAS NOTIFIED: REPORT #408-833. AT APPROX 1530 HRS ON 10/24/`1997 OES WAS NOTIFIED: REPORT #974256 WITHIN 30 DAYS OF THE INCIDENT A COPY OF THIS REPORT WILL BE SENT TO RSPA FED DOT AND CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL. NOTE ON 10/28/1997 I WAS CONTACTED BY MARV HANSEN, DIVISION HEALTH AND SAFETY MANAGER FOR THE TRANSPORTER AND SUPPLIED WITH COPIES OF WEIGHT TICKETS FORM SIMILAR SHIPMENTS OF API/DAF SLUDGE ON 10/20/1997, 10/27/1997 AND 10/28/1997 ALL WITH DISCREPANCIES & OR -320 LBS. THIS LATEST INFORMATION OF 10/28/1997 WOULD INDICATE THAT AGENCY NOTIFICATION MAY OR MAY NOT HAVE BEEN NECESSARY AND IF SO THE AMOUNT OF MATERIAL SPILLED COULD NOT BE DETERMINED. IF YOU HAVE ANY FURTHER QUESTION CONCERNING THIS EVENT, I CAN BE REACHED AT THE ABOVE LOCATION.

AT TIME DELIVERY, ONE PAIL FOUND WITH A FORK HOLE IN ITS SIDE. NO SIGN OF ANY ESCAPE OF CONTENTS. PAIL PLACED INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT FOR RETURN. ALL PAILS ARE DESCRIBED AS BEING IN POOR CONDITION. CONSIGNEE REJECTED ENTIRE SHIPMENT.
WHEN THE FREIGHT WAS BEING UNLOADED THE PAILS WERE DROPPED CAUSING A LEAK AROUND THE TOP AND LOSS OF APPROX. 1.5 GALLONS. LIDS WERE RESEATED TO STOP LEAKAGE AND FREIGHT WAS DELIVERED.

column168: A SMALL AMOUNT OF GASOLINE APPEARS TO HAVE LEAKED THROUGH THE CAP OF THE INNER GLASS BOTTLE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

THIS SHIPMENT LEAKED AT OUR ANCHORAGE FACILITY.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS IT WAS EIGHT PLASTIC BOTTLES INSIDE A FIBREBOARD BOX INSIDE THE PAPER FEDEX LETTER ENVELOPE DESIGNED FOR DOCUMENTS.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (SEE ENCLOSED) WAS OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE FLASH POINT IS 119 DEGREES FARENHEIT; PER IATA DEFINITION  A PACKING GROUP III FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THE ORAL TOXICITY RAT LD 50 NUMBER ON THE MSDS IS LISTED AS 460 MG/KG; PER IATA DEFINITION THIS IS A 6.1 TOXIC IN PACKING GROUP III (FOR LIQUIDS).  TABLE 3.10 IN IATA FOR PRECEDENCE OF HAZARDS REQUIRES THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID TO BE THE PRIMARY HAZARD IN THIS INSTANCE AND THE TOXIC THE SUBRISK (FOR BOTH PACKING GROUP III MATERIALS).  THUS, AS THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT PACKAGED, MARKED, LABELED, OR DOCUMENTED AS DANAGEROUS GOODS, IT IS BELIEVED TO BE "FLAMMABLE LIQUID, TOXIC, NOS," UN1992.  THE FAA WAS PHONED BY OUR LOCAL ANCHORAGE OFFICE.  FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE SECOND MSDS ENCLOSED WAS FOR A SECOND PRODUCT, OTHER THAN THE VARNISH WHICH WAS ALSO IN SHIPMENT.

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF NO PACKAGING FAILURE. THE LIQUID OXYGEN DELIVERY VEHICLE WAS PARKED ON A SLOPED PARKING AREA WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY. WHEN THE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED THE DRIVER MANUALLY BEGAN TO VENT DELIVERY PRESSURE FROM THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER DID NOT REALIZE THAT THE VENT LINE WAS BENEATH THE LIQUID LEVEL BECAUSE THE TRAILER WAS PARKED ON A SLOPE. LIQUID EXITED VIA THE VENT LINE THAT WOULD NOT ORDINARILY BE UNDER THE LEVEL OF THE LIQUID PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER. SINCE THIS WAS THE FIRST OF SEVERAL DELIVERIES SCHEDULED FOR THAT DAY, THE VESSEL CARGO TANK WAS STILL NEARLY FULL. LIQUID PRODUCT EXITED THE VENT, WHICH PREVENTED THE DRIVER ROM SHUTTING THE VENT VALVE. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO ASSIST THE DRIVER. THE FIRE CHIEF AND DRIVER DECIDED TO LET THE PRODUCT VENT UNTIL THE LIQUID LEVEL WAS BELOW THE VENT LINE. THE VENTING PROCEEDED WITHOUT INCIDENT; WHEN THE LIQUID STOPPED FLOWING OUT OF THE VENT, THE DRIVER SHUT THE MANUAL VENT VALVE AND SECURED THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO HIS NEXT DELIVERY WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

WHEN THE SHIPPER LOADED THEIR TRAILER, THEY LOADED CYLINDERS STARTING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THIS PUT CYLINDERS THROUGH THE AREA OF THE RIGHT SIDE LOADING/UNLOADING GATE. WHILE IN ROUTE THE SHIPPERS TRAILER FRAME TWISTED WHILE IN A LEFT HAND TURN. THE TWISTING MOTION OF THE TRAILER CAUSED THE "LATCH-PIN" TO FALL OUT OF THE RIGHT SIDE GATE ALLOWING IT TO COME OPEN. WHEN THE GATE CAME OPEN, FOUR (4) OF THE CYLINDERS THAT WERE BEING CARRIED IN FRONT OF THE GATE FELL OFF AND STRUCK THE GROUND. UPON IMPACT THEIR VALVES SHEARED OFF CAUSING THE LOSS OF PRODUCT FROM THE FOUR (4) CYLINDERS. THE SHIPPERS TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO A REPAIR SHOP WHERE REPAIRS TO THE RAIL AND GATES WERE MADE. THE SHIPPER NOW HAS WRITTEN  A LOADING PROCEDURE WHICH PROHIBITS PLACING AND SECURING CYLINDERS IN ANY GATE AREA. JACK B. KELLEY, INC HAS INSTRUCTED THEIR DRIVERS OF THE SHIPPERS LOADING PROCEDURES AND THE DRIVERS ARE TO INSPECT THE LOAD FOR COMPLIANCE BEFORE LEAVING THE PICK-UP POINT.

PARTY #2 WAS TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON STATE ROUTE 51 IN THE #2 LANE AT APPROXIMATELY 55 MPH.  THE VEHICLE #1, THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER COMBINATION, DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT, ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY.  THE TRACTOR STRUCK THE GUARD RAIL ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE ROADWAY.  THE VEHICLE TRAVELING UPON AND THEN OVER THE GUARD RAIL WITH THE RIGHT TIRES.  THE VEHICLE, STILL TRAVELING NORTH BOUND, STRUCK THE CONCRETE A STREET BRIDGE SUPPORT, AND IMMEDIATELY BECAME ENGULF IN FLAME. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER CONTINUED IN A NORTHERN DIRECTION, UNDER THE A STREET BRIDGE.  THE TRAILER OVERTURNED.  PARTY #2 UPON SEEING THIS, SWERVED INTO THE #1 LANE NORTH BOUND STATE ROUTE 51 AND ACCELERATED THROUGH THE FLAMES, COMING TO A STOP NORTH OF THE COLLISION AND FIRE SCENE.  BASED ON STATEMENTS AND PHYSICAL EVIDENCE.

column168: ON OPERATIONS DATE 10-1-90 ,P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN WAYNE HOGSETT AND I (BEN TAYLOR) RESPONDED TO A CALL OF A LARGE BOX LEAKING A BROWNISH LIQUID THAT HAD AN ODOR OF PAINT. UPON ARRIVAL TECHNICIAN HOGSETT AND I DONNED CARTRIDGE MASK AND APPROACHED THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION.  AFTER WALKING AROUND THE PACKAGE TO SEE IF THERE WERE ANY MARKINGS OR LABELS THAT MIGHT INDICATE  IF THE PACKAGE CONTAINED ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WE DID NOT SEE ANY LABELS, SO WE OPENED THE PACKAGE AND DISCOVERED TWO INNER WHITE FIBERBOARD BOXES THAT WERE UN SPECIFICATION UN4G/Y28/S/95, AND WERE MARKED WITH THE ABOVE PROPER SHIPPING NAME AND TECHNICAL NAME ON EACH THEY WERE ALSO LABELED AS POISON AND SUBSIDIARY LABEL CLASS 3 (FLAMMABLE). THESE TWO INNER BOXES HAD ORIENTATION ARROW PRE-PRINTED ON EACH OPPOSITE SIDES OF EACH BOX.  WE THEN OPENED BOTH BOXES AND DISCOVERED 2 X 2 1/2 GAL PLASTIC JUGS OF DURSAN 275 PESTICIDE FOR A TOTAL OF 5 GALLONS EACH BOX.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A LARGE PLASTIC BAG THEN WE OVERPACKED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION 85 GALLON DRUM AND TAKEN TO OUR HAZMAT SORT FACILITY AND PUT INTO OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL THE FAA INVESTIGATES AND RELEASED BY THE FAA.
THE PAIL WAS DROPPED AT UNLOAD.  EXAMINATION OF THE PAIL REVEALED A PUNCTURE WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE PAIL WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

column168: WORE PROPER PPE, FOLLOWED DECISION TREE, USED CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, PH1. NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE, ABSORBED LIQUID WITH CLAY BASED ABSORBANT. DISPOSED OF WASTE THROUGH DMP PROGRAM.

BRAD WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKY PACKAGE ON THE SORT AISLE.  UPON ARRIVAL BRAD NOTICED A CORROSIVE LIQUID LABEL ON IT.  BRAD DONNED ALL OF THE APPROPRIATE PPE AND REFERRED TO THE CORROSIVE LIQUIDS RESPONSE SHEET.  AN INITIAL PH OF 2 WAS TAKEN AND SODIUM BICARBONATE WAS ADDED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL.  A SECOND READING OF 7 WAS OBTAINED.  THE BOX ABSORBED THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE DAMAGED PORTION WAS PROCESSED IN THE DMP AND THE REMAINDER WAS SENT ON.

AT 7:15, I SETH UPHAM, NOTICED A LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE PRELOAD BELT.  I NOTICED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS A DOT HAZARDOUS.  THE DOT LABEL SAID HARMFUL (STOW AWAY FROM FOODSTUFFS), I COULD NOT READ THE FIVE PART.  USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET  I RESPONDED WITH A SPILL CART AND PPE.  MARK ANDERSON WAS MY BACKUP FOR SCBA. AT 7:20, AFTER GETTING THE SPILL CAR AN PPE, I RETURNED TO PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS 20 FEET FROM DMP AREA AND MYSELF AND MARK ANDERSON RESTRICTED THE AREA.  I THEN PROCEEDED TO PLACE THE LEAKING PACKAGE INTO A SPILL TUB AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH CLAY ABSORBENT.  I THEN RETURNED TO THE DMP AREA AND PROCESSED THE SPILL ACCORDING TO THE DAMAGED MATERIALS PROGRAM. FOUND THAT THE PACKAGE FAILED BECAUSE OF IMPROPER PACKAGING (IS: A GLASS BOTTLE WITH INSUFFICIENT CUSHIONING).  RECOMMEND FOLLOW UP WITH SHIPPER TO PROVIDE ADEQUATE CUSHIONING IN FUTURE SHIPMENTS.  COMPLETED CLEANUP AND DOCUMENTATION AT 10:15.

column168: ONE 10/14/1997 MY CREW INFORMED ME OF A STRONG ODOR INSIDE OF THE AIRCRAFT.  I WENT UP TO CHECK IT OUT AND DISCOVERED THAT NOT ONLY WAS THERE A STRONG SMELL BUT ALSO SOME TYPE OF IRRITANT CAUSING MY EYES TO BURN.  AFTER FINDING THE CONTAINER WITH THE ODOR I HAD IT REMOVED FROM THE A/C. THE "C" CONTAINER WAS THEN MOVED TO THE GROUND SO I COULD UNLOAD IT TO FIND THE LEAKER.  THE PKG WA FOUND AT 17:15 - AT THIS TIME I CONTACTED ALDRICH CHEMICAL AT THE HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM FROM DIA.  THE BUILDING WAS EVACUATED AND NO ONE RETURNED UNTIL THE OK WAS GIVEN BY LT WINTERS OF THE DENVER FIR DEPT.

FREIGHT WAS PICKED UP AT UPJOHN AROUND 1:00 PM ARRIVING FRITZ RAMP AT AROUND 3:00 PM WHERE A DRIP OF LIQUID WAS DETECTED OVER THE RIGHTHAND REAR WHEELS OF THE TRUCK.  THE SOURCE OF SAME WAS FOUND TO BE A SMALL PUNCTURE ON THE BOTTOM RIM OF ONE OF THE DRUMS EVIDENTLY CAUSED BY A PROTRUDING NAIL HEAD FROM THE WOODEN SKID WHERE THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED ON.  LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED AND DRUM TRANSFERRED TO ISOLATED AREA IN OUR WAREHOUSE.  NOTICEABLE ODOR REMAINED IN THE TRUCK AS WOODEN FLOOR WAS SOAKED WITH LIQUID.  FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED.  AT 3:15 PM FIREMAN LANDRAU AND OSORIO WHOM CALLED THEIR SPECIALIZED HAZMAT UNIT WHICH ARRIVED AT 3:45 PM UNDER COMMAND OF LT. MOJICA THEY SECURED THE AREA AND ORDERED EVACUATION.  MEANWHILE WE NOTIFIED UPJOHN 24 HR EMERGENCY CONTACT NO. WHERE MR. RAY STANNARD LOGGED OUR CALL AT 3:20 PM.  WE ALSO NOTIFIED MRS. CENTENO AND MR. NATALICIO WITH UPJOHN PR PLANT. MESSAGE WAS LEFT TO MR. JUAN BULTED OF LOCAL FAA OFFICE, HE WAS INFORMED OF SITUATION WHEN HE CALLED BACK AT AROUND 4:00 PM. CLOSE TO 5:00 PM ARRIVE MR. DANIEL ROSADO FROM THE PR ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY BOARD WHO TOOK CHARGE OF PROCEDURES FROM THEREON.  CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES WERE PERFORMED BY CROWLEY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES CREW LEADER BY MR. FRANCISCO SUZAO AND SUPERVISED BY MR. ROSADO (PREQB).  CROWLEY ENVIRONMENTAL SVC ACTED CONTRACTED BY UPJOHN PR UNDER JOB NO. 3248.  ALL MATERIAL AND DEBRIS WAS COLLECTED BY CROWLEY AND RETURNED TO UPJOHN ALONG WITH REMAINING (UNHARMED) DRUMS.  CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED TO THE SATISFACTION OF MR. ROSADO PROCESS STARTED AT 6:15 PM AND ENDED AT 9:45 PM. NO PERSONAL INJURIES RESULTED OF THE INCIDENT.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW, DURING INSPECTION OF TANK CARS AT BRADY, NE, NOTED ODOR COMNG FROM STUFFING BOX PACKING GLAND, TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. REPACKED STUFFING BOX AND TIGHTENED PACKING GLAND, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. JOE BABAR, CHEMTREC #60693 AND PAT RASMUSSEN, WESTEC PETROLEUM, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT RICHARD CARMAN NOTIFIED AT 1700 HRS ON 10/1/97 TANK CAR # GATX 33884 CONTAINING STYRENE MONOMER, INHIBITED WAS LEAKING AT PINE BLUFF, AR. IN THE YARD. MANAGER CTS RICHARD TUFTS NOTIFIED BY ENVIRONMENTAL DIRECTOR STEVE BERKI AT 1940 HRS THAT AGENT CARMAN WAS ON SCENE OF ACCIDENT AND HAD REDUCED THE LEAK EMITTING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE, HOWEVER TANK WAS STILL LEAKING. MANAGER TUFTS ARRANGED AIR TRANSPORT AND ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 2300 HRS. NOTING INTERNAL PRESSURE OF TANK CAR TO BE 47 LBS AND LEAK STOPPED. MANAGER TUFTS AND AGENT CARMAN CONTACTED SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE TOM LAMBRIGHT, AMOCO, AND DISCUSSED CIRCUMSTANCES OF THIS INCIDENT. IT WAS TUFTS AND CARMANS BELIEF THAT THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED AND THAT PRODUCT VOLUME WOULD HAVE TO BE REDUCED. HAZ-TECH ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE WAS CONTACTED AND RESPONDED WITH STAINLESS STEEL VAC TRUCK TO OFFLOAD PRODUCT. HAZ TECH WAS RETAINED BY AMOCO FOR THIS INCIDENT. APPROXIMATELY 1500 GALS OF PRODUCT WAS OFFLOADED FROM TANK CAR AND WAS RETURNED TO THE POINT OF ORIGIN, TEXAS CITY, TEXAS. CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION. THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOST WAS ESTIMATED AT APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS. THERE WAS NO PRODUCT LOSS IN THE TRANSFER PROCESS.

column168: WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS IN THE OGDEN UT. YARD. MGR. RODABOUGH NOTED A STRONG ODOR OF MTBE. INSPECTION OF THREE CARS ON SPOT AT THAT LOCATION, REVEALED CAR NATX 37687 HAD AN AUDIBLE VAPOR LEAK AROUND THE MANWAY COVER. MGR. RODABOUGH TIGHTENED ALL 8 BOLTS, STOPPING THE LEAK.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS IN THE OGDEN UTAH, YARD MANAGER H.W. RODABOUGH, NOTED TANKCAR UTLX 14862, A LOADED CAR OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID. WITH PRODUCT RUNNING DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR. INSPECTION REVEALED A BROKEN BLIND FLANGE ON THE VAPOR VALVE. THE FLANGE WAS MADE OF GRAY PLASTIC ABOUT THREE QUARTER INCH THICK. MANAGER RODABOUGH WENT TO DYCE CHEMICAL AND PROCURED ANOTHER FLANGE AND APPLIED IT TO THE CAR AND WASHED THE CAR WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND WATER. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  MGR. RODABOUGH NOTIFIED CHEMTREC, MR. TOM WARNICK, OF THE DETAILS AND HE ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 60793. MR. ROB MATTESON (503) 225-7263) OF ELF ATOCHEM WAS ALSO ADVISED OF THE CIRCUMSTANCES.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS IN THE OGDEN UT. YARD. MGR. RODABOUGH NOTED FLAT CAR CP520502 WITH ROLL-OFF CONTAINER CHIU 24111, WITH PRODUCT SPILLING OUT OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE FLATCAR AND ONTO THE STEPS AND SAFETY APPLIANCES. MGR. RODABOUGH CALLED THE SHIPPER CLEANHARBORS AT THEIR CINCINNATI OFFICE, (800-805-4582) AND INFORMED THEM REGARDING THE SITUATION. THEY ASKED IF MGR. RODABOUGH COULD CLEAN THE CAR AND PUT THE SPILLED PRODUCT BACK INTO THE CONTAINER, THEN APPLY SOME TYPE OF SORBENT MATERIAL TO STOP THE LEAKAGE. MGR. RODABOUGH CALLED PACIFIC WEST AND ARRANGED FOR A CREW TO CLEAN THE CAR AND STOP THE LEAK AND RETURN THE PRODUCT TO THE CONTAINER. REMEDIATION TO BE COMPLETE BY THE END OF THE DAY, FRIDAY THE 3RD OF OCTOBER. MGR. RODABOUGH NOTIFIED CHEMTREC, MR. TOM WARNOCK, FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 60795. MGR. RODABOUGH ALSO NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER CLEANHARBORS AND SPOKE WITH MR. JOHN STEVENS (800-805-4582). RECEIVED IN INTERCHANGE - PER 49CFR 172.205(F) - NO MANIFEST AVAILABLE.

column168: REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, SPARKS, NV., WHILE CONDUCTING TRAINING WITH LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES AT WABUSKA, NV., WAS ADVISED BY MEMBER LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT ROQUE LOPEZ, EMPLOYEE OF BULK TRANSPORTATION, STOCKTON, CA, WHILE UNLOADING TANK CARS AT WABUSKA, NW. WAS SPLASHED WITH SULFURIC ACID FROM TANK CAR PVCX 13489. HE WAS TREATED BY EMERGENCY MEDICAL TECHNICIANS AND TRANSPORTED TO HOSPITAL BY BULK TRANSPORTATION TRUCK DRIVER MIKE BROWN. WHITELEY CONTACTED TRUCK DRIVER DOUG DONLAN, BULK TRANSPORTATION, WHO WAS AT THE SCENE; HOWEVER, HE ADVISED THAT HE HAD NOT WITNESSED THE INCIDENT. HOWEVER, HE WAS TOLD THAT THE UNLOADING HOSE WHICH WAS PLACED INTO FILL HOLE ON HIGHWAY CARGO TANK HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY SECURED AND DISLODGED FROM FILL HOLE DURING LOADING OF TRUCK AND SPLASHED LOPEZ. INSPECTION OF SCENE NOTED SPILLED ACID ON TOP OF TANK CAR PVCX 13489 AND ON GROUND ON NORTH SIDE OF TANK CAR WHERE HIGHWAY CARGO TANK WAS PARKED. I INSTRUCTED DONLAN THAT TANK CAR WOULD HAVE TO BE DECONTAMINATED AND IMPACTED SOILS CLEANED UP. CONSIGNEE OF TANK CAR CONTRACTS BULK TRANSPORTATION TO HAUL ACID AND PLANT MANAGER TRAVIS CANTWELL, ARIMETCO, 702-463-3125 WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF CLEAN UP NEEDS.

REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L. WHITELEY, SPARKS, NV., WAS NOTIFIED BY RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER, DENVER, CO., THAT TANK CAR NATX 37241, DENATURED ALCOHOL, SPOTTED PHOENIX YARD, PHOENIX, AZ, WAS LEAKING. CONTACTED DAN SAUSITO, YARDMASTER, AND SAM KEPHERT, MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, WHO ADVISED LIQUID WAS FLOWING DOWN SIDES OF TANK CAR FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR IN THE AREA OF THE MANWAY. THE PHOENIX FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SCENE. WHITELEY REQUESTED AND RECEIVED TELEPHONE CALL FROM PHOENIX FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO ADVISED LIQUID WAS COMING FROM VERTICAL VALVE ASSEMBLY ON TOP OF TANK CAR AND AFTER DISCUSSION IT WAS DETERMINED THE RELEASE ORIGIN WAS SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS PREPARING TO MAKE ENTRY AND THE SUGGESTION WAS MADE TO ATTEMPT TO RELIEVE INTERNAL PRESSURE IN CAR THRU THE AIR VALVE. ALSO CONSIDERATION SHOULD BE MADE TO REDUCE LIQUID LADING FROM CAR IF TANK CAR WAS OVER LOADED. WHITELEY REQUESTED CALL BACK FROM FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHICH WAS NEVER RECEIVED. WHITELEY CONTACTED SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE JOHN WOHLGEMUTH FOR ANY RESOURCES AVAILABLE AT CONSIGNEE, WITH NEGATIVE RESULTS. REPEATED CONTACTS WITH OPERATING OFFICERS AT SCENE DEVELOPED THE LIQUID FLOW FROM SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD SLOWED DOWN. ALSO, A TRUCK WAS ENROUTE TO REDUCE LADING. AT 1835 HOURS SAM LEPHERT ADVISED THAT RELEASE HAD STOPPED AND ATTEMPTED TO MOVE TANK CAR TO CONSIGNEE UNLOADING FACILITY FOR OFF LOADING. CHEMTREC BOB WIBLE WAS FURNISHED ALL DETAILS AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT NUMBER 60859. AT THE TIME OF THIS INCIDENT AMBIENT TEMPERATURE IN PHOENIX WAS 100 DEGREES F. SPILLED MATERIAL THAT IMPACTED GROUND IMMEDIATELY EVAPORATED.

UPRR EMG COORDINATOR NORM SILER REPORTED THAT BOX CAR UP460008 WAS ON FIRE IN ODESSA YARD, TX. UPRR MTO KEITH NORRIS AND ODESSA FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ON SCENE. THE YARD WAS SHUT DOWN BECAUSE OF THE HOSES AND PERSONNEL ACROSS THE TRACKS. THE CAR DOORS WERE OPENED AT THE SCENE BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ACCESS THE FIRE. APPROXIMATELY 4 PALLETS OF BAGGED SULFUR WAS INVOLVED. IT IS NOT KNOWN HOW MANY INDIVIDUAL BAGS WERE INVOLVED. PALLETS WERE SHRINK-WRAPPED.

column168: MANAGER CTS RICHARD TUFTS RECEIVED NOTIFICATION BY PAGER FROM RISK MANAGEMENT DISPATCH CENTER AT 0415 HOURS.   ON 10/15/97 THAT CAR #EDCX 6003, CAR LOAD OF NITRIC ACID HAD BEEN FOUND TO BE EMITTING VAPOR AND WAS BEING SET OUT ON THE SIDING AT FLINTON, IL., MANAGER TUFTS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND WHILE ENROUTE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, ELDORADO CHEMICAL, MR. GERALD MARTIN, HOME PH# 870-863-1452, CEL #870-510-6278, PAGER # 870-863-2932 TO ADVISE SITUATION. UPON ARRIVAL AT SCENE APPROXIMATELY 0830 HRS., MANAGER TUFTS OBSERVED A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF VAPOR BEING RELEASED FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE CAR. MANAGER TUFTS APPROACHED THE CAR IN APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE GEAR AND OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING NOTING A VERY LIGHT RESIDUE OF FLUID ON THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. MANAGER TUFTS CHECKED ALL NUTS, ALL VALVES AND CLOSURES, AND FOUND ALL TO BE TIGHT WITH NO DETECTABLE LEAKAGE. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, MANAGER TUFTS DETERMINED THAT 6 MANWAY COVER PLATE BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND WERE ALLOWING VAPOR TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE PLATE SEAL. MANAGER TUFTS TIGHTENED THE 6 BOLTS WHICH STOPPED THE VAPOR RELEASE. TANK PRESSURE WAS DETERMINED TO BE 2 LBS. MANAGER TUFTS RESECURED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER AND CONTACTED SHIPPER TO ADVISE STATUS. CORRIDOR MANAGER AND RISK MANAGEMENT DISPATCH CONTACTED TO ADVISE CAR SECURE AND READY TO MOVE TO DESTINATION.

column168: DRIVER S. IZATT CALLED FROM DMR IN OSAGE BEACH AND SAID THAT HE HAD A HAZ MAT PKG LEAKING IN HIS TRUCK. I TOLD HIM TO STAY PUT, I WOULD BE RIGHT THERE . I GOT MY GLOVES, APRON, BOOTS, AND GOGGLES AND PUT THE PACKAGE INTO A DAMAGE TUB AND CLEANED UP THE REST OF THE CARGO AREA. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGE BACK TO THE BUILDING TO PROCESS THE PACKAGE. I FOLLOWED THE DMP PROCESS AND USED PROPER PPE TO CLEAN UP, FILLED OUT ALL REPORTS AND FOLLOWED DMP PROCEDURES TO NEUTRALIZE THE PRODUCT AND DISPOSE OF RESIDUE.

column168: ON 10/25/97 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT SUPERVISOR, SCOTT THOMPKINS REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR AT THE HAZMAT SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR, INC. PART-TIME HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIANS, MATT GROVESNOR AND CHRIS CAHPPA RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED,  TECHNICIAN CHAPPA DONNED A SELF COUNTING BREATHING APPARATUS AND STRUCTURAL FIR FIGHTING GEAR TO INVESTIGATE.  INSIDE WERE THREE INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES THAT CONTAINED GLASS RECETPACLES.  EACH GLASS RECEPTACLE AND CREW TYPE CLOSURE. THERE WAS POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH ROOM FOR OUTAGE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON 10-11-97 SORT SUPERVISOR, JAY WALRAVEN REPORTED A SHIPMENT LEAKING IN THE MAIN SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR, INC.  PART-TIME HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED.  PART-TIME TECHNICIAN WILLIAMS PLACED SOME PH PAPER ON THE LIQUID.  THIS PAPER BECAME RED, WHICH INDICATED THIS WAS AN ACID.  UPON INVESTIGATIONS OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX IT WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN AN AUTOMOBILE BATTERY.  ONE OF THE CLOSURES ON THE BATTERY CAME LOOSE ALLOWING SOME OF THE LIQUID CONTENTS TO LEAK.  THERE WAS NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THESE CLOSURE.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS.  LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZMAT SORT IN THE SECURITY CAGE, PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RECEIVED  A CALL FROM ROGER SPUTZ, MANAGER, TERMINAL OPERATIONS, EAST YARD, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA REPORTING A TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THE CAR WAS OBSERVED LEAKING WHILE BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE STUB TRACK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE EAST YARD, AND OBSERVED THE BOTTOM OUTLET DRIPPING AT A RATE OF 5 DROPS PER MINUTES.  THE LIQUID WAS ESCAPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE WHERE THE OUTLET CAP IS THREADED ON.  THE UNDERCARRIAGE OF THE "A" END OF THE CAR WAS COVERED WITH PRODUCT, INDICATING IT HAD BEEN DRIPPING FOR SOME TIME WHILE IN TRANSIT.  UPON INSPECTING THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPERATING HANDLE, FOUND THE PACKING GLAND LOOSE AND WAS ABLE TO TURN THE VALVE HANDLE A FULL ONE AND A HALF TIMES.  ONCE THE VALVE WAS SECURED, THE LEAK CEASED. THE PACKING GLAND WAS SECURED, AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. DUE TO MINIMAL AMOUNT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L WHITELEY, SPARKS, NV  WHILE MAKING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTION WINNAMUCCA, NV  OBSERVED SPILLAGE RIGHT SIDE TANK CAR NATX 76187.  INSPECTIONS NOTED HINGED MANWAY COVER LID PROTECTED BY INTACT SEAL PROC UT 01852.  NOTED MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS BROKEN AND PROTRUDING FROM UNDERNEATH HINGED MANWAY COVER LID.  THIS WAS THE POINT OF RELEASE OF PRODUCT AND IT WAS OBVIOUS THAT TANK CAR HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY SECURED AT POINT OF ORGIN.  BROKEN GASKET WAS REPLACED AND SEAL UPF 329867 WAS APPLIED FOR PROTECTION. ALSO NOTED CAR BILLED TO CONTAIN COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID AND WAS DISPLAYING FLAMMABLE LIQUID PLACARDS.  ALL 4 PLACARDS WERE REPLACED.  CONTACTED DOUG FOSTER, CRYSEN REFINING, WOODS CROSS, UT., WHO ADVISED TANK CAR HAD BEEN LOADED FOR THEM BY PHILLIPS PETROLEUM, WOODS CROSS, IT. FURTHER HE WOULD CONTACT LISA VOLERIO, PHILLIPS PETROLEUM, REGARDING EXCEPTIONS.
TANK CAR INSPECTION REVEALED LOOSE LIQUID SECURING CAP.  CAP WAS SECURED AND CAR ALLOWED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION.

ACCOUNTING LEAKING.  CONTACTED SPECIAL AGENT/ HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SIL MARTINEZ, POCATELLO, ID  WHO RESPONDED AND UPON ARRIVAL NOTED TANK CAR WAS STILL LEAKING FROM FLANGE ASSEMBLY LOCATED FRANGIBLE DISK HOUSING.  ATTEMPT TO STOP LEAK BY TIGHTENING FLANGE BOLTS WAS UNSUCCESSFUL ACCOUNT CONDITION OF SECUREMENT NUTS AND BOLTS.  IT WAS NECESSARY TO APPLY WASHERS TO SHIM BOLTS SO THEY COULD BE TIGHTENED. THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY A FIRM FROM SALT LAKE CITY, UT WHO LATER REPORTED TO SAHM MARTINE THAT CAR HAD BEEN INSPECTED AND WAS OK FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

MANAGER R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED AT 1615 HOURS 10-26-97 BY CARMAN HOGAN CODA THAT CAR PTRX 7006 WAS LEAKING.  MR STINE ARRIVED ON SITE AT THE 18TH STREET YARD AT 1630 HOURS AND NOTED ICE BUILD UP ON THE VAPOR VENT PIPE.  REMOVED CABLE SEAL FROM CABINET DOOR AND THE CAR STARTED EXCESSIVE VENTING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. CAR WAS BILLED AS "RESIDUE LAST CONTAINER ETHYLENE, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, 2.1, UN1038. PRODUCT BEING FLAMMABLE AND EASILY IGNITED ADVISED MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS TO STOP SWITCHING ACTIVITY IN THE AREA.  CONTACTED CHEMTREC REQUESTING SHIPPER CONTACT.  ALSO NOTIFIED KANSAS CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT REQUESTING THEIR HAZ MAT RESPONSE UNIT. UPON ARRIVAL OF KANSAS CITY FIRE APPROACHED THE CAR AND NOTED THE VALVE HAD RE-CLOSED WITH ONLY A VERY SLIGHT "HISSING" BEING NOTED.  PASSPORT GAS DETECTOR INDICATED THAT DURING THE RELEASED FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE A READING OF 5% OF THE  AT THE CAR HOWEVER AFTER THE VALVE RESET NO DETECTIBLE READING WAS NOTED.  SR MTO JIM COX ARRIVED AND THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED SO THAT YARD SWITCHING COULD CONTINUE.  MR. JIM GILLESPIE, EMERGENCY RESPONSE SPECIALIST OF THE HUNTSMAN CORPORATION AND MR. PAT GIBSON BAKER PERFORMANCE CHEMICAL, AND MR STEVE NICKLES OF PETROLITE CHEMICAL ALL DISCUSSED WITH MR STINE OPTIONS.  MR GILLESPIE AND BOB ACAFEE RESPONDED TO THE SITE 10-27-97 AND DEVELOPED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR TO BE 73 PSI AND INDICATED THIS CAR WOULD HAVE A PRESSURE INCREASE OF 1.95 POUND PER DAY.  FELT THE BEST OPTION TO MAKE THE CAR SAFE WAS TO FLARE THE VAPOR AND REDUCE THE PRESSURE.  ARRANGEMENT WERE MADE TO SET UP FLARING OPERATION 10-28-97.  NOTIFIED OFFICE OF MICKEY DAVIS, WYANDOTTE COUNTY EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS, MR. GARY BLACKBURN KDHE OF THE OPERATION.  ALSO KANSAS CITY FIRE HAZMAT CHIEF ED DRIPP.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER HAD BEEN ADVISED BY MR. GILLESPIR.  AFTER OBTAINING THE MATERIAL NEEDED FOR THE OPERATIONS WITH KANSAS CITY HAZ MAT TEAM WITH ONE PUMPER STANDING BY STARTED THE FLARE AT 1225 HOURS AND FLARED UNTIL THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS AT 9PSI.  THE PRESSURE REDUCTION FROM 73 PSI TO 5 PSI WAS COMPLETED AT 1345 HOURS.  CAR IS A DOT 113 C 102 W CAR HAVING BEEN BUILT 8/70, SAFETY VALVE TESTED AT 75 PSI 943, DUE  99, TWO FRANGIBLE 116LB DISC INSTALLED 9-97 DUE 9-98. STENCILLED LIQUID CAPACITY 32152 GALLONS.,  FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  THE LIQUID VALVE HANDLE WAS OFF THE CALVE LAYING IN CABINETS LEFT SIDE "A" END.  TWO OF FOUR FLANGE BOLTS WERE LOOSE ON THE VENT STOCK FLANGE.  THE "VACUUM CAN" LOCATED ON THE "B" END HAD TWO BOLTS MISSING.  THESE EXCEPTIONS HAD NOTHING TO DO WITH THE PRESSURE BUILDING ON THE RESIDUE CAR.  HAD NO WAY TO CHECK THE VACUUM ON THIS CAR IN THE FIELD.  THE CAR HAD BEEN REROUTED TO "AMKO" DOVER, OHIO FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR.

THE PRESSURE REDUCTION FROM 73 PSI TO 5 PSI WAS COMPLETED AT 1345 HOURS. THESE EXCEPTIONS HAD NOTHING TO DO WITH THE PRESSURE BUILDING ON THE RESIDUE CAR.  HAD NO WAY TO CHECK THE VACUUM ON THIS CAR IN THE FIELD. AOC DRIVER WAS RETURNED TO DRIVING AFTER 8 HOUR BREAK.  THE DRIVER DID A PRE - TRIP INSPECTION AND EVERYTHING SEEMED TO BE IN ORDER.  THE DRIVER HAD MANUALLY CHECKED THE CAPS PRIOR TO LEANING THE PLANT.  WHEN THE DRIVER CAME OFF AN 8 HOUR BREAK, HE VISUALLY CHECKED THE CAPS.  THE DRIVER HAD GONE APPROX.  15 TO 20 MILES BEFORE COMING TO A TRAFFIC SIGNAL.  THERE WAS A CURVE IN THE ROAD.  HE BEGAN TO SLOW DOWN.  HE CAME TO A COMPLETE STOP AT THE RED LIGHT.  A DRIVER IN A PASSENGER VEHICLE PULLED UP ALONG SIDE OF THE A O C DRIVER.  THE DRIVER OF THE PASSENGER VEHICLE ASKED THE A O C DRIVER WHAT HE WAS HAULING. HE TOLD THE A O C DRIVER  THAT HE WAS LEAKING.  THE A O C DRIVER TOLD THE DRIVER HE WAS HAULING REISIN.  THE LIGHT CHANGED AND BOTH DRIVERS PULLED OVER TO A GRAVEL AREA.  THE A O C DRIVER GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND INSPECTED THE PASSENGER VEHICLE. THERE WAS RESIN COATING THE WINDSHIELD AND SPOTTING THE REST OF THE CAR.  THE A O C DRIVER INSPECTED TANKER.  MOST OF THE RESIN WAS ON THE FRONT OF THE TANKER.  THE A O C DRIVER CLIMBED UP THE TANKER LADDER.  THE A O C DRIVER SAW THE INSIDE OF THE RUPTURED DISK LAYING ABOUT A FOOT AND A HALF FROM THE 3 INCH VENT CLEAN OUT.  THE A O C DRIVER AT THAT TIME CLIMBED DOWN THE LADDER AND CALLED THE TRANSPORTATION SUPERVISOR.  WE GOT THE GENTLEMANS INFORMATION.  I TOLD THE GENTLEMAN TO GET AN ESTIMATE ON THE PAINT JOB HE WILL BE GETTING. I GAVE HIM THE NUMBER TO CONTACT ME.  THE DRIVER OF THE PASSENGER VEHICLE CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  A STATE TROOPER SHOWED UP AR THE SCENE .  THE STATE TROOPER SAID THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THEIR WAY.  THEY WOULD BE THERE SHORTLY.  THE TROOPER LOOKED AT THE PASSENGER VEHICLE.  THE A O C DRIVER ASKED THE TROOPER IF HE WOULD LIKE TO SEE THE PAPER WORK AND THE TROOPER SAID THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WOULD TAKE CARE OF IT.  THE TROOPER DIRECTED TRAFFIC AND WAITED ON THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED.  THE FIREMAN ASKED FOR THE PAPERWORK AND PLACARD NUMBER. THE FIREMAN LOOKED AT THE PAPER WORK AND THE SPILL.  HE TOLD THE STATE TROOPER THAT THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH SPILLED TO WORRY ABOUT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.   THE FIRE DEPARTMENT LEFT.  THE STATE TROOPER TOLD THE A O C DRIVER THAT THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH RESIN SPILLED TO WORRY ABOUT AND HE LEFT THE SCENE.  THE A O C DRIVER GOT GASOLINE AND TRIED TO CLEAN THE WINDSHIELD OF THE PASSENGER VEHICLE.  THAT DID NOT WORK.  THEY GOT LIQUID HAND SOAP AND THAT DID NOT WORK.  AFTER SCRUBBING THEY GOT A SMALL PLACE CLEAR ENOUGH FOR THE DRIVER TO DRIVE THE VEHICLE HOME.  I DISPATCHED A DRIVER IN THE AREA TO BRING THE OTHER A O C DRIVER CAP.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM ON OCTOBER 20, 1997, WHILE DRIVING EAST ON ROUTE I-80, ANOTHER DRIVER CALLED THE HAZMAT DRIVER ON THE CB RADIO AND NOTIFIED HIM THAT SMOKE WAS EMANATING FROM HIS TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY LOOKED FOR A SAFE PLACE TO PULL OVER AND FOUND A WIDE SHOULDER NEAR EXIT 58. AFTER HE STOPPED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER, HE WALKED AROUND THE TRAILER. HE SAW SMOKE. HE FELT THE SIDES OF THE TRAILER AND THEY WERE NOT HOT. HE THEN RETURNED TO THE TRACTOR. HE FIRST ATTEMPTED TO REACH THE STATE POLICE ON CHANNEL 9 OF HIS CB RADIO. FAILING TO CONTACT THE POLICE, HE TURNED TO CHANNEL 19 AND ASKED IF SOMEONE WITH A CELL PHONE WOULD CALL 911. HE RECEIVED A CALL BACK THAT 911 HAD BEEN CALLED. HE THEN UNHOOKED THE TRACTOR FROM THE TRAILER AND MOVED THE TRACTOR AWAY FROM THE TRAILER. AT THIS TIME, THE FIRST POLICE OFFICER ARRIVED. AT APPROXIMATELY 3:10 PM HE USED A CELL PHONE TO CALL HAZMATS OFFICE IN BUFFALO. AT APPROXIMATELY 3:20 PM MR DENNIS DINTINO, PRESIDENT OF HAZMAT, CALLED NANCY BEEBE OF THE LAIDLAW-BDT FACILITY IN CLARENCE, NEW YORK. SHE ADVISED MR DINTINO THAT LAIDLAW WOULD MAKE ARRANGEMENTS FOR A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR TO BE DISPATCHED TO THE SITE. AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30 PM HAZMAT SPOKE AGAIN WITH NANCY BEEBE AT LAIDLAY-BDT WITH FURTHER INFORMATION REGARDING THE SITUATION. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:10 PM NANCY BEEBE ADVISED HAZMAT THAT JOHN MCNALLY FROM LAIDLAW WAS PROCEEDING TO THE SCENE. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:50 PM MR WALTER JANICEK FROM THE NEW JERSEY BUREAU OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, CALLED HAZMAT REGARDING MOBILIZING A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM ON OCTOBER 20, 1997, WHILE DRIVING EAST ON ROUTE I-80, ANOTHER DRIVER CALLED THE HAZMAT DRIVER ON THE CB RADIO AND NOTIFIED HIM THAT SMOKE WAS EMANATING FROM HIS TRAILER. HE IMMEDIATELY LOOKED FOR A SAFE PLACE TO PULL OVER AND FOUND A WIDE SHOULDER NEAR EXIT 58. AFTER HE STOPPED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER, HE WALKED AROUND THE TRAILER. HE SAW SMOKE. HE FELT THE SIDES OF THE TRAILER AND THEY WERE NOT HOT. HE THEN RETURNED TO THE TRACTOR. HE FIRST ATTEMPTED TO REACH THE STATE POLICE ON CHANNEL 9 OF HIS CB RADIO. FAILING TO CONTACT THE POLICE, HE TURNED TO CHANNEL 19 AND ASKED IF SOMEONE WITH A CELL PHONE WOULD CALL 911. HE RECEIVED A CALL BACK THAT 911 HAD BEEN CALLED. HE THEN UNHOOKED THE TRACTOR FROM THE TRAILER AND MOVED THE TRACTOR AWAY FROM THE TRAILER. AT THIS TIME, THE FIRST POLICE OFFICER ARRIVED. AT APPROXIMATELY 3:10 PM HE USED A CELL PHONE TO CALL HAZMATS OFFICE IN BUFFALO. AT APPROXIMATELY 3:20 PM MR DENNIS DINTINO, PRESIDENT OF HAZMAT, CALLED NANCY BEEBE OF THE LAIDLAW-BDT FACILITY IN CLARENCE, NEW YORK. SHE ADVISED MR DINTINO THAT LAIDLAW WOULD MAKE ARRANGEMENTS FOR A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR TO BE DISPATCHED TO THE SITE. AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30 PM HAZMAT SPOKE AGAIN WITH NANCY BEEBE AT LAIDLAY-BDT WITH FURTHER INFORMATION REGARDING THE SITUATION. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:10 PM NANCY BEEBE ADVISED HAZMAT THAT JOHN MCNALLY FROM LAIDLAW WAS PROCEEDING TO THE SCENE. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:50 PM MR WALTER JANICEK FROM THE NEW JERSEY BUREAU OF EMERGENCY RESPONSE, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, CALLED HAZMAT REGARDING MOBILIZING A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY. HAZMAT IMMEDIATELY CALLED NANCY BEEBE WITH THIS INFORMATION. SHE CONFIRMED AGAIN THAT LAIDLAW WAS MAKING ARRANGEMENTS FOR THE CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR AND SHE WAS CONSULTING WITH OTHER LAIDLAW PERSONNEL. SHE SAID THAT SHE WOULD CALL BACK. AT APPROXIMATELY 6:15 PM NANCY BEEBE ADVISED HAZMAT THAT LAIDLAW HAD HIRED S & D ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AS THE CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR. AS A RESULT OF THE STEEL CONTAINMENT FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, LITTLE MATERIAL FROM THE FIRE ESCAPED TO THE GROUN. THE RESIDUE AND REMAINING DRUMS WERE PACKAGED AND DELIVERED TO THE BDT FACILITY IN CLARENCE, NEW YORK. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PLACED IN A ROLL-OFF BOX WHICH WAS DISPOSED OF BY S & D ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES AND LAIDLAW. THE TRAILER WAS TRANSPORTED TO A LAIDLAW FACILITY AT DYANOKEM, DETROIT, MICHIGAN FOR DISPOSAL.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: AT APPROX 10:08 AM ON OCT 27, 1997 THE DRIVER JOHN BESSLER WAS UNLOADING A 330 GAL TOTE AT ANGELICA HEALTH SERVICES. THE NORMAL UNLOADING PROCEDURE AT THIS ACCOUNT IS TO LOWER THE LIFT GATE TO THE GROUND, THE LIFT OPERATOR, WILL THEN DRIVE HIS FORK LIFT ONTO THE LIFT GAT RAMP TO RETRIEVE THE TOTE FROM INSIDE THE TRAILER. THIS IS DONE TO ALLOW THE OPERATOR TO PLACE HIS FORKS COMPLETELY UNDER THE TOTE BEFORE BACKING OUT. THE FORK LIFT OPERATOR PROCEEDED  TO DRIVE ONTO THE PLATFORM AND LIFTED THE TOTE INTO THE AIR AND STARTED TO BACK OUT, AS THE TOTE CLEARED THE TRAILER IT SHIFTED SLIGHTLY TO THE RIGHT AND HESITATED FOR A SECOND, THEN STARTED TO FALL TO THE RIGHT SIDE. THE DRIVER RAN TO THE FRONT OF THE TRACTOR AND CLEARED THE AREA OF THE SPILL. WHEN HE RETURNED THE FORK LIFT OPERATOR WHO  ALSO HAD RUN FROM THE SCENE WAS RETURING FROM THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE TRAILER THE TOTE WAS SITTING ON ITS TOP AND FORK LIFT (UNATTENDED) WAS STILL MOVING BACKWARDS APPROX 25 FEET AWAY. THE LIFT OPERATOR MOUNTED HIS FORK LIFT, AND PROCEEDED TO PLACE THE FORK UNDER THE TOTE WHICH WAS NOW FACING THE GROUND, AT THIS TIME THE TOE WAS STILL INTACT. LIFTING THE TOTE ON ONE SIDE HE LET THE TOTE FALL ON ITS SITE (FALL #2). THE TOTE WAS LEAKING THE TOTE SLIPPED OFF THE FORKS AND HIT THE GROUND AGAIN (FALL#3) SPLITTING THE TOTE ON THE TOP PORTION (SEE PICTURE). THE LIFT OPERATOR WAS SPLASHED AND HAD BLEACHED HIS EYES. JOHN BESSLER (DRIVER) INSTRUCTED THE OPERATOR TO USE WATER OR EYE WASH FOR HIS EYES. HE DID NOT SEEM TO UNDERSTAND AND JOHN FOUND ANOTHER EMPLOYEE TO INTERPRET THIS INSTRUCTION. THE LIFT OPERATOR WAS SENT TO THE MEDICAL CLINIC AND WAS RELEASED FOR WORK , BUT LATER IN THE WENT HOME EARLY. ANOTHER EMPLOYEE WIDENED THE FORKS TO GIVE EQUALLY DISTRIBUTE THE WEIGHT AND LIFTED THE TOTE TO THE UPRIGHT POSITION. (SHOULD HAVE BEEN DONE BY THE FIRST OPERATOR). NOTE, THE TOTE WAS APPROX 18 INCHES FROM THE GROUND WHEN THE TOTE SLIPPED FOR THE THIRD TIME.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THE FREIGHT WAS AN INBOUND CASH ON DELIVERY (COD).  AS THERE WAS NO INDICATOR ON THE COD BILL OF LADING TO INDICATE HOW MUCH WAS OWED ON THE PACKAGE, FEDEX OPS MGR BILL DAIGER OPENED THE BOX.  UPON OPENING THE BOX BILL FOUND SEVERAL STEEL CANS AND PLASTIC BOTTLES.  IT APPEARED THE PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD LEAKED.  IN ADDITION, THE BOX CONTAINED A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  THE MSDS CLEARLY IDENTIFIED THE MATERIAL AS PAINT, UN1263 WITH A FLASHPOINT OF 115 DEGREES F.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  I SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER, TIM COUNIHAN, SUPERVISOR FOR SMALL PRODUCTS.  I ADVISED WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND HE INDICATED THAT THEY HAD A PROCESS IN PLACE TO ENSURE THIS WOULD NOT OCCUR.  TIM INDICATED THAT HE HAD A NEW EMPLOYEE IN SHIPPING AND MUST HAVE INADVERTENTLY MISSED THE TRIGGER THAT INDICATED THIS WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS.  I HAVE CALLED THE SFO CASFO & LEFT A MESSAGE WITH THE RECEPTIONIST FOR A CALL BACK ON THIS CASE. THE FREIGHT WILL BE HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: THIS BOX WAS PLACED ON THE FLOOR DURING THE SORT.  IT SPILLED.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS, IT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE A FIRE EXTINGUISHER WHICH HAD DISCHARGED ITS CONTENTS.  THE PACKAGE WAS NOT PACKAGED, MARKED, LABELED, OR DOCUMENTED AS DANGEROUS GOODS.  AS IT IS BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS, NAMELY, "FIRE EXTINGUISHERS.  UN1044, I PHONED FAA AGENT DAVE KING AT (202)768-2918.  PROPER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED AND FEDEX WILL HOLD THE PACKAGE PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. I WAS UNABLE TO REACH THE SHIPPER AT THE PHONE NUMBERS WE HAD LISTED IN OUR COMPUTER SYSTEM FOR THEIR ACCOUNT NUMBERS; IT SIMPLY RANG INDEFINITELY.  I WAS ALSO UNABLE TO GET A LISTING FROM DIRECTORY ASSISTANCE SO I WAS NOT ABLE TO INFORM THE SHIPPER OF THE PROBLEM WITH PACKAGE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: HVH DRIVER, WILLIAM MAYO, PICKED UP A PARTIAL LOAD FROM ASHLAND CHEMICALS, PUEBLO, CO AT APPROXIMATELY 0530 WEDNESDAY OCTOBER 29, 1997. THE TWO SHIPMENTS ON THE REFRIGERATED TRAILER WERE DESTINED TO TWO CUSTOMERS IN COLORADO SPRINGS, CO. MAYO PROCEEDED NORTHBOUND ON I-25 ENROUTE TO COLORADO SPRINGS AFTER DEPARTING ASHLAND'S FACILITY IN PUEBLO. AT THE 107 MILE MARKER (MM) MAYO DROVE OVER A LARGE PATCH OF ICE (APPROXIMATELY 40 FT) UNDER A RAILROAD OVERPASS. THE PAVEMENT WAS DRY PRIOR TO AND AFTER THE AREA UNDER THE OVERPASS.  AFTER PROCEEDING UNDER THE OVERPASS MAYO ENCOUNTERED A SCENE WHERE A PASSENGER CAR HAD SPUNOUT AND CAME TO REST IN THE MEDIAN BETWEEN THE NORTH AND SOUTHBOUND LANES OF I-25. FROM FACTS DERIVED FROM WITNESS STATEMENTS MAYO DROVE OVER THE PATCH OF ICE AND LOST CONTROL. MAYO'S TRAILER STARTED SPINNING TO HIS RIGHT, TURNED 180 DEGREES AND ENTERED THE MEDIAN TRAILER REAR FIRST IN THE SAME AREA AS THE CAR. DUE TO A STEEP EMBANKMENT FROM THE SHOULDER TO THE BOTTOM OF THE MEDIAN AREA THE TRAILER OVERTURNED, WHICH IN TURN CAUSED THE TRACTOR TO OVERTURN. A DIAGRAM FROM THE INVESTIGATING OFFICER FROM THE COLORADO STATE PATROL IS ATTACHED. DUE TO THE FORCES OF THE OVERTURN ACCIDENT PRODUCTS IN THE TRAILER WERE THROWN ABOUT AND CRUSHED. APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS LEAKED FROM ONE 55 GALLON POLY RUBBER DRUM OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (UN 2014). APPROXIMATELY .5 GALLONS LEAKED FROM A POLY BOTTLE OF SULFURIC ACID (UN 1830). APPROXIMATELY .5 GALLONS OF ETHANOLAMINE SOLUTION (UN2491) LEAKED FROM A POLY BOTTLE. FINALLY, APPROXIMATELY 10-15 GALLONS OF #2 DIESEL LEAKED FROM THE RIGHT FUEL TANK OF THE TRACTOR. DUE TO THE AMOUNT OF SNOW REMAINING IN THE MEDIAN AND THE MINIMAL AMOUNTS OF LEAKAGE FROM ALL CONTAINERS NO PRODUCT OR SOIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE ACCIDENT SCENE AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT. HOWEVER, THE COLORADO DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH HAS NOT CLOSED THE FILE; THE NEED FOR SCENE RESTORATION COULD STILL OCCUR.  OFFICER PULVER OF THE COLORADO STATE PATROL AND DEPUTY BLACKBURN OF THE PUEBLO COUNTY SHERIFF'S OFFICE WERE EXPOSED TO THE SULFURIC ACID FUMES. BOTH WERE ADMITTED TO ST. MARY CORWIN HOSPITAL FOR OVERNIGHT OBSERVATION. BOTH RELEASED THE NEXT MORNING WITH NO ILL EFFECTS NOTED. SUBSEQUENT FOLLOWUP FOR BOTH INDICATED NO LINGERING OR LONGTERM EFFECTS.

column168: ON TUESDAY, OCTOBER 21, 1997 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:20AM A CALL CAME OVER THE MINE RADIO FROM THE DIXON BROS. FUEL DRIVER TO BILL PEDERSEN. THE DRIVER INFORMED BILL THE LARGE FUEL TANK AT THE IN-PIT FUEL ISLAND HAD RUPTURED & SPILLED FUEL. DRIVER'S INFO IS AS FOLLOWS: ROY ALLAN CUMMINGS - EMPLOYED BY DIXON BROS. APPROXIMATELY 5 YEARS AS DRIVER 217 4TH AVENUE NEWCASTLE, WY 746-3311 - HOME PHONE 746-2788 - DIXON BROS. DISPATCH PHONE. TOM MCGRATH MET BILL PEDERSEN & LARRY OLSON AT THE IN-PIT FUEL ISLAND. THEY OBSERVED THE LARGE "LAY DOWN" TANK ON THE NORTH END OF THE FUEL COMPOUND HAD THE EAST END OF SAID TANK PEELED BACK FROM THE MAIN TANK BODY; THE WELD ALONG THE NORTH EDGE SEPARATED AND THE WELD ALONG THE SOUTH EDGE REMAINED INTACT. APPROXIMATELY 95% OF THE SPILLED FUEL WAS CONTAINED IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA. HOWEVER DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE RUPTURE, THE POSITION OF THE TANK AND THE MANNER IN WHICH THE END SPLIT FROM THE TANK BODY, THE MAIN FLOW OF FUEL WAS DIRECTED TOWARDS THE CONTAINMENT BERM, AND SOME FUEL DID SPLASH OVER THE BERM ON THE NORTHEAST SIDE. THIS FUEL STARTED TO RUM DOWN A DRAINAGE AREA. THE SPILL FUEL WAS BLOCKED OFF USING THE 117 LOADER TO DUMP SEVERAL LOADS OF DIRT AHEAD OF THE SPILL. THE AREA WAS CONED OFF. TOM MCGRATH CALLED CHRIS ZAVADA (ELECTRICIAN ON DUTY) AND HAD HER DISCONNECT ALL POWER TO THE FUEL STORAGE AREA. KISSACK WATER SERVICE WAS CONTACTED TO SEND OUT SEVERAL VAC TRUCKS TO START EVACUATING THE LIQUID INSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA BEFORE IT SOAKED INTO THE GROUND. STEVE STORIE, CRAIG JENNINGS, STEVE BURCHETT AND JACK LAAKSO WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. MR. CUMMINGS NOTIFIED DIXON BROS. DISPATCH OF THE INCIDENT AS WELL. AFTER AN INITIAL INVESTIGATION, IT IS ESTIMATED APPROXIMATELY 1,500 GALLONS OF FUEL SPLASHED OUTSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA. MR. CUMMINGS STATED THE TANK HAD APPROXIMATELY 9' (13,613 GALLONS) SHOW ON THE GAUGE PRIOR TO HIM BEGINNING TO OFF-LOAD FUEL. HE ALSO STATED THE TANK SHOULD HAVE BEEN ABOUT FULL AT THE TIME OF THE RUPTURE. THE FUEL DELIVERY TICKET FOR 10-21-97 SHOWED 11,001 GALLONS BEING DELIVERED TO THE MINE SITE. BY CALCULATING OUT THE BEFORE AND AFTER TANK LEVELS AT THE MAIN TANK FARM NEAR THE SHOP, THE DRIVER APPARENTLY OFF-LOADED 9.959 GALLONS OF FUEL INTO THE MAIN TANK FARM. THEREFORE, HE OFF-LOADED APPROXIMATELY 1,042 GALLONS AT THE IN-PIT FUEL ISLAND BEFORE THE RUPTURE.

column168: DURING UNLOADING PROCESS A WORKER NOTICED A CARTON WAS CRUSHED BY HEAVY FREIGHT IN TRANSIT.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC CONTACTED.  AN MSDS REQUESTED. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HRS ON WEDNESDAY 16, OCTOBER, MANAGER HARRY W RODABOUGH RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FRO SPECIAL AGENT KEITH SNUFFIN AT POCATELLO REGARDING A LEAKING TRAILER, BMDZ632500. INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER CONDUCTED AT 0800 HRS ON 17, OCTOBER IN COMPANY WITH MR ED BANKS, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT ONE OR POSSIBLY TWO OF THE FIVE GALLON PAILS HAD BEEN CRUSHED, SPILLING THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINERS. ALL LEAKING HAD STOPPED AND THE PRODUCT HAD CURED LEAVING A SOLID EPOXY LIKE FILM ON THE CAR AND INSIDE THE TRAILER. FURTHER INSPECTION OF SHIPPING PAPERS AND CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, CONSPEC MARKETING AND MANUFACTURING CO., INC REVEALED THAT THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS COPNSPEC #1-21% SOLIDS. USED TO CURE AND DUST PROOF AND SEAL AGED CONCRETE. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF BLOCKING OR BRACING AND THE FULL LOAD HAD SHIFTED TO THE BACK OF THE CONTAINER AND HAD TO BE REPOSITIONED. THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY THE CAR DEPT. USING PETIBONE CRANE. ALL WORK COMPLETE AT 1400 HRS ON THE SAME DATE. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED, MR JOE BABER FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 61341. THE SHIPPER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED. MR ALAN HUNTER OF CONSPEC ALSO INFORMED.

column168: UPRR CAR FOREMAN REPORTED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR ACFX 17315, RESIDUE. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET CARTER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE WAS LEAKING. THE HANDLE WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION. THE LIQUID AND VAPOR PLUGS WERE LOOSE. ALSO, THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE CAR WAS STENCILED "LEAKY CAR DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIRED" ON BOTH SIDES AND THE DEFECTIVE VALVE WAS MARKED. DALE JOHNSON, FARMLAND, WAS ADVISED VIA CHEMTREC.

REICHHOLD CHEMICALS, INC. DRIVER, BOBBY STRICKLAND,ARRIVED AT MORSE MANUFACTURING AND IDENTIFIED HIMSELF TO THE OWNER, MR. MORSE, AND GAVE HIM THE BILL OF LADING.  HE MENTIONED TO MR. MORSE THAT HIS ORDER WAS FOR 40,000 LBS, BUT THAT THE LOAD CONTAINED 42,260 LBS. WHEN IT WAS TIME TO UNLOAD, THE DRIVER WAS TOLD BY THE RECEIVER (THE OWNER'S BROTHER) TO PULL INTO THE UNLOADING DOCK.  THE OWNER, MR. MORSE, TOOK A STICK AND MEASURED THE DEPTH OF THE MATERIAL ON THE GROUND AND WALKED OFF THE LENGTH AND WIDTH OF THE SPILL. HE CALCULATED THE CUBIC FEET TO DETERMINE HOW MANY POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.  HE THEN LOOKED UP THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY IN HIS HAZ MAT BOOK AND TOLD THE DRIVER THAT THE SPILL WAS UNDER THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY, WHICH IS A LITTLE OVER 3,000 POUNDS.  HE TOLD THE DRIVER THAT HE CALCULATED THE SPILL TO BE 200 GALLONS.  THE RECEIVER THEN CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND UPON THEIR ARRIVAL THEY PUT DOWN OIL DRY. IT IS RECCOMMENDED THAT THE CUSTOMER (MORSE MANUFACTURED.)  REDESIGN THEIR VENT SYSTEM. ALSO, OUR DRIVER RECOMMENDS THAT THE CUSTOMER PLACE AND AUDIBLE ALARM ON THEIR PRESENT SYSTEM, SINCE IN THE DAYLIGHT HOURS, THEIR PRESENT CLEAR-COLORED LIGHT DOES NOT DRAW THE IMMEDIATE ATTENTION OF THE DRIVER.
RESPONDED IN THE SORT AISLE WEARING PPE, USING DECISION TREE IDENTIFIED PACKAGE AS CORROSIVE WITH PH OF 13.  USING THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, THROUGH DMP PROGRAM.

PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO DMP CAGE BY KELLY BARTON, RESPONDER, I USED DECISION TREE, USED PPE, IDENTIFIED AS CORROSIVE WITH A PH OF 3, USED CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET, NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBENATE, ABSORBED WITH DRY ALL. PROCESSED THROUGH DMP. THIS PACKAGE HAD NO OUTSIDE LABELING.
USED RESPONSE SHEET FOR CORROSIVE LIQUID. USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE. THEN USED SPEEDI TO CLEANUP SPILL. DAMAGE PORTION SENT TO DMP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

UNDECLARED MATERIALS OFFERED BY PASSENGER WERE WRAPPED SO AS TO COVER DANGEROUS GOODS LABELS. PACKAGE BROKE OPEN DURING LOADING. SPILL OF 1 - 3 CUPS OF MATERIAL WAS CLEANED. AIRCRAFT DELAYED ONE HOUR, PASSENGER AND CREW TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER AIRCRAFT. COUNTY LAW ENFORCEMENT AND FBI NOTIFIED UPON DISCOVERY OF FAILURE TO DECLARE BY SHIPPER/PASSENGER. MANUFACTURER LABEL INDICATED MATERIALS WERE PH 8 CORROSIVE; TO DATE, WE ARE UNABLE TO CONFIRM ACTUAL CORRECTIVELY OF CHEMICAL.

HOLE WAS PATCHED AND DRUM WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  RECOVERY DRUM CONTAINING CLEANUP DEBRIS WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT A LATER DATE.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER LOCATED IN SPACE # 261, ALONG TRACK #805. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF FACILITY AND LOCATED THE CONTAINER ACTUALLY SITTING IN THE EAST ROADWAY ALONG TRACK #805. THE REAR OF THE 20 FOOT CONTAINER WAS RESTING ON THE PAVEMENT, WITH THE FORWARD PORTION STILL ON THE CHASSIS. THE FRONT PORTION OF THE CHASSIS WAS STILL ATTACHED TO A STREET TRACTOR OPERATED BY MR. MENDOZA, WHO WAS DRIVING FOR MSL. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE CHASSIS TO DISTRIBUTE THE WEIGHT OVER HIS AXLES PRIOR TO DEPARTING THE FACILITY. IN THE PROCESS OF LOCKING THE CHASSIS BRAKES, AND PULLING FORWARD TO STRETCH THE FRAME LOCKING PINS BYPASSED THE FORWARD PORT OPENINGS AND TORE THE STOP PLATES OFF, ALLOWING THE CHASSIS TO COME APART AND THE CONTAINER TO DROP TO THE PAVEMENT. THIS SEPARATION APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY OVER SPEED AND DRIVER NOT PAYING ATTENTION. THE CONTAINER IMPACTING THE PAVEMENT CAUSED THE LADING OF 55 GALLON DRUMS TO LEAK, AND APPROXIMATELY 50-60 GALLONS OF METHANOL HAD BEEN RELEASED THROUGH THE REAR DOORS ONTO THE PAVEMENT. THE LIQUID WAS DIKED AND CONTAINED, THEN DILUTED WITH WATER TO SUPPRESS THE VAPORS. THE AREA WAS THEN COVERED WITH ABSORBENT AND SWEPT UP FOR CONTAINMENT IN DRUMS. THE CONTAINER WAS PICKED UP AND PLACED ONTO A NEW CHASSIS AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INSPECTION. UPON OPENING THE CONTAINER, OBSERVED METAL 55 GALLON DRUMS, BANDED TO PALLETS, AND DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT THE CONTAINER. TY-PATCH MATERIAL WAS USED TO SECURE THE LADING AND APPEARED TO BE PROPERLY APPLIED. THE FLOOR LOADED DRUMS HAD SUSTAINED HEAVY DAMAGE FROM THE IMPACT AND THE ADDITIONAL WEIGHT OF THE SECOND TIER DRUMS. IN ORDER TO INSPECT THE DRUMS AND LOCATE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK, THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER REQUIRED REMOVAL. DURING THE REMOVAL PROCESS, LOCATED ONE DRUM ON THE FLOOR STACK, SECOND FROM THE RIGHT SIDE, IN THE FIRST ROW AT THE DOORWAY, THAT WAS SEVERALLY DISTORTED AT THE BOTTOM CHIME, ALLOWING AN EIGHT INCH SEPARATION BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AND THE CHIME. THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE DRUM HAD BEEN LOST. IN ALL, A TOTAL OF 35 ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION. ALL WERE PLACED INTO OVER PACKS FOR SECUREMENT. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE MANUFACTURER TO REPLACE THE DAMAGED DRUMS, AND THE CONTAINER WAS RELOADED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER TO FACILITATE RECOUPING OF THE PRODUCT. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC ADVISING UPRR SENIOR CLAIMS REPRESENTATIVE, GENE HINNANT REPORTED A SWITCHMAN HAD BEEN SPLASHED BY ACID (INCIDENT 1097LAO12) FROM A LEAKING TANK CAR WHILE MAKING A JOINT IN THE BOWL #220 TRACK WITHIN THE COLTON YARD. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD AND MET WITH ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER, TOM BEESE, AND LOCATED THE SUSPECT TANK IN YARD TRACK #317, WHERE IT HAD BEEN MOVED TO ISOLATE PENDING INSPECTION. INSPECTION NOTED THE GASKET FROM THE 12 INCH HOLE COVER PLATE WAS TORN AND COMPLETELY BLOWN OUT FROM UNDER THE COVER PLATE. IT WAS FOUND RESTING ON TOP OF THE COVER PLATE. THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE FILL HOLE COVER PLATE SECURED. FURTHER INSPECTION FOUND THE FRANGIBLE DISC BURST IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND MODEL WITH BAFFELS, ADJACENT TO THE FILL HOLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE BS & B 100 LB. STAINLESS/ TEFLON DISC. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE. THE CAR SURFACE AND IMMEDIATE GROUND AREA WERE NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER EXPOSURES.

During loading, a "fuel" odor was noticed by the ground crew.  The subsequent investigation led to the discovery of several containers of STP Diesel Treatment.  One of the containers was leaking and the fumes were emitting through the bag.  The material was confiscated and the passenger continued to his destination.  The cargo compartment was checked for residual fluid and vapors, and the aircraft was released.
